[[Category:Medical databases|OneKey]]

'''Pinopods''' (also known as '''pinopodes''' and '''uterodomes''') are apical [[epithelium|epithelial]] [[Cell (biology)|cellular]] protrusions of the [[endometrium]] of the [[uterus]].<ref>Adams, SM et al. Manipulation of the follicular phase: Uterodomes and pregnancy - is there a correlation? BMC Pregnancy and Childbirth (2001) 1:2 http://www.biomedcentral.com/content/pdf/1471-2393-1-2.pdf</ref>
Pinopods have a [[pinocytosis|pinocytotic]] role (hence the name pinopod - Greek for "drinking foot"), as well as a secretory role,<ref>Kabir-Salmani, M et al. Secretory role for human uterodomes (pinopods): secretion of LIF. Molecular Human Reproduction 2005 11(8):553-559 http://molehr.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/full/11/8/553</ref> however their usefulness as a marker for endometrial receptivity is still debated in the current literature.<ref>Quinn, CE and Casper, RF. Pinopodes: a questionable role in endometrial receptivity. Human Reproduction Update 2009 15(2):229-236 http://humupd.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/15/2/229</ref>
Pinopods also absorb uterine fluid, this 'suction' effect, brings the blastocyst nearer to the endometrium and immobilise it. ==References== {{Reflist}}
[[Category:Mammal female reproductive system]] [[Category:Human female reproductive system]]
{{Developmental-biology-stub}}

'''Plant expressed vaccine''' or '''project GreenVax'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibioinc.com/press/iBio%20GreenVax%20Licensing%20Release%202-26-10%20Final.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-08-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100524183445/http://www.ibioinc.com/press/iBio%20GreenVax%20Licensing%20Release%202-26-10%20Final.pdf |archivedate=2010-05-24 |df= }}</ref> In 2005 [[DARPA]]’s Accelerated Manufacture of Pharmaceuticals (AMP) program was created In response to emerging and novel biologic threats.<ref>http://www.nonaiswa.org/?p=5465</ref> In 2009 [[DARPA]] offered a government contract for a [[Genetically modified food|Non-GMO]] plant-based systems expressing recombinant proteins, due to The 2009 H1N1 [[swine flu]] pandemic that highlighted the national need for rapid and agile vaccine manufacturing capabilities.<ref name="DARPA">{{cite web|url= http://www.darpa.mil/dso/solicitations/DARPA-SN-09-59.doc| title=Scalable Manufacturing of Plant-Expressed Vaccines|publisher=DARPA | =|accessdate=Aug 2010}}</ref> The [[Texas A&M University]] and a Texas company have been awarded a $40 million U.S. [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] grant to develop a plant expressed vaccine made from tobacco.<ref name="Houston Chronicle" /> While egg-based vaccines typically take more than six months to develop after a virus is isolated, the new process will take only four to six weeks.<ref name="Houston Chronicle">{{cite web|url= http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/metropolitan/6882706.html| title=A&M gets big grant to make tobacco-based vaccine|publisher=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=Aug 2010}}</ref> The vice chancellor for research at A&M System declared that if the project works it will be one of the largest and most capable vaccine facilities in the world.<ref name="Houston Chronicle"/> However the major problem is the public acceptance of this technology, many of the companies are looking for the FDA approval <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agbioforum.org/v8n4/v8n4a05-kirk.htm|title=Social Acceptance of Plant-Made Vaccines: Indications from a Public Survey|last=McIntosh|first=Dwayne D. Kirk and Kim|date=2006-01-24|website=www.agbioforum.org|access-date=2018-04-03}}</ref>
The plant-based vaccine production method works by isolating a specific antigen protein, one that triggers a human immune response from the targeted virus. A gene from the protein is transferred to bacteria, which are then used to “infect” plant cells. The plants then start producing the exact protein that will be used for vaccinations.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wired.com/dangerroom/2010/02/darpa-funded-researchers-tobacco-vs-viral-terror/ | work=Wired | first=Katie | last=Drummond | title=Darpa-funded Researchers: Tobacco vs. Viral Terror | date=24 February 2010}}</ref> Other uses of plant-expressed vaccines including the successful creation of edible bananas that protect against the [[Norwalk virus]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wired.com/dangerroom/2010/02/darpa-funded-researchers-tobacco-vs-viral-terror/#ixzz0vqkU1NqL | work=Wired | first=Katie | last=Drummond | title=Darpa-funded Researchers: Tobacco vs. Viral Terror | date=24 February 2010}}</ref>
