'''Rapid growing mycobacterium''' consists of organism of the [[Mycobacterium fortuitum]] group and [[Mycobacterium chelonae]]/[[Mycobacterium abscessus]] group<ref name="pmid19929702">{{cite journal |vauthors=Esteban J, Ortiz-Pérez A |title=Current treatment of atypical mycobacteriosis |journal=Expert Opin Pharmacother |volume=10 |issue=17 |pages=2787–99 |date=December 2009 |pmid=19929702 |doi=10.1517/14656560903369363 |url=http://informahealthcare.com/doi/abs/10.1517/14656560903369363}}</ref> and these usually cause subcutaneous [[abscesses]] or [[cellulitis]] following trauma in immunocompetent patients.<ref name="Andrews">{{cite book |author1=James, William D. |author2=Berger, Timothy G. |title=Andrews' Diseases of the Skin: clinical Dermatology |publisher=Saunders Elsevier |location= |year=2006 |pages= |isbn=0-7216-2921-0 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=|display-authors=etal}}</ref>{{rp|340}}
==List of rapidly growing Mycobacteria== *[[Mycobacterium fortuitum]] *[[Mycobacterium chelonae]] *Mycobacterium smegmatis *[[Mycobacterium abscessus]] *Mycobacterium mucogenicum *Mycobacterium peregrinum
